  "prompt": "Why does pubic and body hair stop growing after it reaches a certain length?",
  "response": "Pubic and body hair stop growing after reaching a certain length due to the biology of hair growth cycles. Hair growth undergoes three main phases: anagen, catagen, and telogen.\n\n1. **Anagen Phase**: This is the active growth phase, during which hair cells rapidly divide, and the hair grows longer. The duration of the anagen phase varies depending on the type of hair. For scalp hair, this phase can last several years, allowing hair to grow quite long. However, for body and pubic hair, the anagen phase is much shorter, lasting only a few weeks to a few months. This limited growth period is why these hairs do not grow as long.\n\n2. **Catagen Phase**: This is a transitional phase lasting a few weeks, during which hair growth stops, and the hair follicle shrinks. This phase marks the end of the active growth of a hair strand.\n\n3. **Telogen Phase**: In this resting phase, the hair follicle is inactive, and the hair eventually falls out. The follicle then remains dormant for a period before the cycle restarts with the anagen phase.\n\nThe length of the anagen phase for body and pubic hair is genetically predetermined and varies among individuals. This phase determines how long a hair can grow before it stops and eventually sheds. As a result, body and pubic hair are naturally limited in length compared to scalp hair.",
